text:
thank you @bluecollarjew for sharing your #rosiestory
.
.
up until december 2016, i was pretty healthy. my whole life changed with a diagnosis of idiopathic intracranial hypertension, the elevation of pressure on the skull pushing on the brain. my life immediately turned upside down with mris, lumbar punctures, blood patches, and doctor appointments.
.
the medications made me so ill i lost 100 pounds and so fatigued that i needed to stop working my then retail job. i took a couple months to recuperate and reflect on what i really wanted to do with my life. i worked on oil rigs, on and off shore. i survived two rapes. i could beat this illness. .
.
i decided to learn to weld. my grandmother welded during wwii and that was my inspiration. i love working with my hands and making things. i earned my aws certificate and got a job at a production facility. i‚Äôm one of two women welders here now and hold my own. i let younger gals know that they can do what i do, too. just like rosie said, ‚Äúwe can do it.‚Äù
.
.
#iamrosie #youarerosie #weareallrosie #riseuprosie #welder #womenwhoweld #wwii #wecandoit #youcandoit #survivor #metoo #idiopathicintracranialhypertension

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby," said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
- what we worked on was ... data harvesting programs where we would pull data from users of apps and all of their friend networks and run that data through algorithms that could profile their personality traits and other psychological attributes, wylie told cnn‚Äôs don lemon monday evening.

wylie said the ultimate goal was to obtain information in order to exploit mental vulnerabilities that our algorithms showed that [facebook users] had.

in addition to wylie and cambridge analytica, accounts of cambridge analytica‚Äôs parent company, strategic communication laboratories, and those of a university of cambridge psychologist aleksandr kogan were also suspended.

the accounts were suspended because facebook received reports that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from kogan‚Äôs app may not have been completely deleted. kogan‚Äôs app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided certifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received reports that, contrary to the certifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending further information.

special counsel robert mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal reported in december. the firm complied to the request.

diana stancy correll
washington examiner

text:
het grote macaulay culkin dossier - dieter de schutter (@dieterdeschutter) uit antwerpen illustreerde voor o.a. de dichtbundel pluimgewicht en het kinderboek het wispelturig windorkest. in 2017 won hij de eerste prijs van greenhouse op het stripfestival @grafixxfest.

voor het online grote macaulay culkin dossier liet dieter zich inspireren door home alone, #metoo en het witte huis... op de grote macaulay culkin avond van de internet gids (dig) op 1 februari zal hij live illustreren! zet jezelf op aanwezig en stap ook in de wondere wereld van mac en dieter! #linkinbio #homealone #trump #macaulayculkin

text:
gop is dead. gop remains dead. and we have killed him. how shall we comfort ourselves, the murderers of all murderers? what was holiest and mightiest of all that the world has yet owned has bled to death under our knives: who will wipe this blood off us? what water is there for us to clean ourselves? what festivals of atonement, what sacred games shall we have to invent? is not the greatness of this deed too great for us? must we ourselves not become gods simply to appear worthy of it?

howlindsey doody

text:
yoni monologues festival 2019 jan 11-13 was a beautiful, heart wrenching, shocking, funny, surprising success. we were proud to once again host an event of this kind after having hosted the vagina monologues at free bird cafe so many years ago. 
all women led, inspired and produced by a team of amazing volunteer actors who stepped up, gave their time and effort and shared some of the deepest parts of the experience of being a woman.

we were able to see the possibilities of our new space hosting an event of this size with about 70 guests each night and actors, staff, and volunteers.. i want to give a huge thank you to our own staff who did their regular jobs while helping out with the vendors and workshop set up and clean up and all of the extra people coming and going, they are amazing üôèüèΩ #communitycenter #communityspace #chiangmai #thailand #veganchiangmi #womensupportingwomen #sustainableliving #freebirdcafe #darkhorsetheatre #outdoortheatre #theatre #communitytheatre #chiangmaicafe #yoniverse #yoni #womenshealing #metoo #metoomovement

a real caring man would not want that anyway!

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

but wylie wasn‚Äôt just talking about fashion. he had recently been exposed to a new discipline: ‚Äúinformation operations‚Äù, which ranks alongside land, sea, air and space in the us military‚Äôs doctrine of the ‚Äúfive-dimensional battle space‚Äù. his brief ranged across the scl group ‚Äì the british government has paid scl to conduct counter-extremism operations in the middle east, and the us department of defense has contracted it to work in afghanistan.

i tell him that another former employee described the firm as ‚Äúmi6 for hire‚Äù, and i‚Äôd never quite understood it.
.
- it‚Äôs like dirty mi6 because you‚Äôre not constrained. there‚Äôs no having to go to a judge to apply for permission. it‚Äôs normal for a ‚Äòmarket research company‚Äô to amass data on domestic populations. and if you‚Äôre working in some country and there‚Äôs an auxiliary benefit to a current client with aligned interests, well that‚Äôs just a bonus.
.
when i ask how bannon even found scl, wylie tells me what sounds like a tall tale, though it‚Äôs one he can back up with an email about how mark block, a veteran republican strategist, happened to sit next to a cyberwarfare expert for the us air force on a plane. - and the cyberwarfare guy is like, ‚Äòoh, you should meet scl. they do cyberwarfare for elections.‚Äô
.
it was bannon who took this idea to the mercers: robert mercer ‚Äì the co-ceo of the hedge fund renaissance technologies, who used his billions to pursue a rightwing agenda, donating to republican causes and supporting republican candidates ‚Äì and his daughter rebekah.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
i've had more days like this than i can count. if you're having one of these days today, please know that it's okay to feel this way. what happened to you was not your fault. i know it hurts, i know the pain feels like it will never go away. and i wish i could tell you it gets better, but the truth is that it doesn't get better, you get better. 
what happened to you was not okay, what was done to you will never be okay. but i can promise you this; if you keep striving to stay resilient, if you keep fighting, if you refuse to let this completely destroy you, you will rise.
there will still be days when the memories knock the breath out of you. 
but you have the strength within you to carry on. whoever hurt you messed with the wrong person. they thought they could burn you, but they didn't know that you were forged in the flames. 
you are a warrior, you will get through this.
üôèüíô

s p i r i t  o f  a  w o m a n
‚Äúevery time women come together in a circle, the world heals a little more.‚Äù
this has certainly been my experience, when connecting with women, sharing with women, opening up with one another in challenging conversations, and allowing ourselves to be vulnerable together. 
as women, we have such a capacity for love, heart connections and sisterhood, and this particular retreat provides a safe and intimate space to get to know ourselves deeper, to explore what may be challenging us, and be in a field of support and acceptance.
allowing this has been such a healing experience in my own journey as a woman. 
the workshop is happening in beautiful byron bay at the end of march. the ocean is nearby, and it‚Äôs a tropical paradise perfect for taking time out for you. 
see the link in my bio for more info.

text:
guilt is an emotional state where we experience conflict at having done something that we believe we should not have done (or conversely, having not done something we believe we should have done). this can give rise to a feeling state which does not go away easily and can be difficult to endure.

if you are experiencing feelings of guilt you are likely to be focussing on something that you have done that is embarrassing, harmful to another person, or some other behaviour which has contributed to negative consequences for you or someone else. sometimes this feeling of guilt can become so big that you may feel overwhelmed and do not have a way to manage the intensity of your feelings. https://youwillbearwitness.com/2019/01/23/do-you-know-enough-about-guilt-so-its-not-holding-you-back-2/ #youwillbearwitness #emdr #erinfado #ptsd #peterfox #ptsdsurvivor #ptsdrecovery #ptsdawareness #stopracism #stopbullying #stopchildabuse #metoo #doitfordolly #trauma #therapydog #dissociativeidentitydisorder

text:
featherweight- one evening,
i sat by the ocean and questioned the moon about my destiny.
i revealed to it that i was beginning to feel smaller compared to others,
because the more secrets of the universe i would unlock,
the smaller in size i became.

i didn‚Äôt understand why i wasn‚Äôt feeling larger instead of smaller.
i thought that seeking truth was what was required of us all ‚Äì
to show us the way, not to make us feel lost,
up against the odds,
in a devilish game partitioned by
an invisible wall.

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby," said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with ficial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

violence against women -the effects of violence can be devastating to a woman's reproductive health as well as to other aspects of her physical and mental well-being. in addition to causing injury, violence increases women's long-term risk of a number of other health problems, including chronic pain, physical disability, drug and alcohol abuse, and depression. women with a history of physical or sexual abuse are also at increased risk for unintended pregnancy, sexually transmitted infections, and adverse pregnancy outcomes. yet victims of violence who seek care from health professionals often have needs that providers do not recognize, do not ask about, and do not know how to address.

text:
i got an exciting phone call today during class. the wonderful victim advocate i have been working with at my university called to let me know that they finally found my attacker who enlisted in the navy. they notified his commanding officer of his past unhealthy behavior with women, and they are going to keep a close eye on him to make sure he doesn't hurt anyone else. i know this may not sound like much, but that is everything that i wanted when i reported. i wanted to make sure he couldn't hurt anyone else the way he hurt me, and now i have done everything i could to make that happen. this has been a long year of back and forward, but the struggle is finally over.

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby," said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

text:
how do i heal
when i still can‚Äôt say the words? 
wishing i could cut out the pieces 
ruined by loving you 
each time i think i‚Äôve reached 
steady ground 
another layer falls away 
raw nerves exposed once again 
seemingly endlessly beginning 
restarting again
and again
and again 
parts of me once soft
sharpened as my mind and heart rage unspoken wars

two sides sitting in tandem 
my mind pedals feverishly 
logic has made peace with all that occurred
only my heart seems unwilling to purge 
unable to fathom the betrayal 
dismayed and disgusted 
moments play on repeat so loudly 
i am certain everyone can see 
remnants of what happened to me
yet the words refuse to spill from my mouth 
white knuckled as i brace for impact
knowing eventually it will break free
pour out of my mouth, molten

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
today i am joined by dr. caroline heldman, badass. dr. heldman is the unsung feminist hero. the gloria steinem of her generation.

what i love about this conversation is that dr. heldman gives us a glimpse into the day to day life of an activist. it is a tough calling, but one that fits her well. we talk the value of data driven arguments as women begin to ask for the pay they deserve and positions of power. we cover the influence media has on our girls and dig into the #metoo and end rape on campus movements.

i‚Äôm glad she is on our side.

as always, please subscribe to this podcast, leave a review and don‚Äôt forget to share with your friends. i‚Äôm always interested in content that uplifts, so if you have things you‚Äôd like to hear about, please share them with me in the comments.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text: lupita nyong‚Äôo has come forward about her encounters with harvey weinstein in an op-ed in the new york times, writing that not only did weinstein attempt to ply her with alcohol when she met with him at a restaurant, but after they moved the meeting to his home to watch a film screening, tried to give her a massage. at a later meeting, the oscar-winning actress wrote weinstein propositioned her in a hotel restaurant. according to nyong‚Äôo, she met with weinstein for the second time ‚Äî after having initially met him in 2011 at an awards ceremony in berlin while she was still in school at yale ‚Äî when he asked her to attend a screening at his home after sharing lunch at a restaurant. when she arrived at the restaurant in westport, conn., where weinstein lived, nyong‚Äôo described weinstein ordering her a vodka soda and insisting that she drink it. ‚Äúharvey told me that i needed to drink the vodka and diet soda. i informed him that i would not,‚Äù she wrote. ‚Äú‚Äòwhy not?‚Äô i remember him asking. ‚Äòbecause i don‚Äôt like vodka, and i don‚Äôt like diet soda, and i don‚Äôt like them together,‚Äô i said. ‚Äòyou are going to drink that,‚Äô he insisted. i smiled again and said that i wouldn‚Äôt. he gave up and called me stubborn. i said, ‚Äòi know.'‚Äùabout 15 minutes into the film, however, weinstein asked her to accompany him outside the room. ‚Äúi protested that i wanted to finish the film first, but he insisted i go with him, laying down the law as though i too was one of his children. i did not want another back-and-forth in front of his kids, so i complied and left the room with him. i explained that i really wanted to see the film. he said we‚Äôd go back shortly. ‚Äúharvey led me into a bedroom ‚Äî his bedroom ‚Äî and him one instead: it would allow me to be in control physically, to know exactly where his hands were at all times.‚Äù nyong‚Äôo wrote that after he removed his shirt and she began giving him a text:
sharing for a friend that's had her story reported and removed by instagram three times... "when i was a little girl i dreamed of falling in love

at age 15, i began to have cyber relations with a 25 year old man. he told me that i was his soulmate and he wanted to urinate on me to profess his love. i ended things because i knew something about it was wrong & he then threatened to kill himself. sergio p.

also at age 15, i had a flashback of an older cousin forcing me to perform oral sex at a very early age. i waited 9 years before asking my mom about it.

at age 16, my first time performing oral sex was through force and intimidation by a college sophomore. javonte m.

also at age 16, i was cornered by 3 other students. they kept laughing about how far aj's fingers would go up my vagina. it was just us. that was one of the scariest moments of my life. luckily the bell rang. kendrick m., aj.

at age 17, a coach at my high school gave me a $100 with a note saying it was going to be our year. he invited me to the movies. jamele h.

at age 18, my first vaginal sex experience was forced by a childhood friend a year older than me. he raped me. afterwards he said "i couldn't let them *** at famu get to you first.... how does it feel to be a woman?" later on i confronted him and he told me i was a liar and that i wanted it. at a much earlier point, he told me that he lost his virginity to a woman at least in her 30's. michael n.

at age 19, i went to a classmates house to tutor him in physics. i got very drunk. he raped me. later on he acknowledged and apologized for his actions. very very healing & therapeutic. as.

from age 18-20 i was involved in an emotionally abusive situation. he asked me how could i be so dumb to get raped twice. sam h.

for the last few years i've had recurring dreams of confronting mike, because his betrayal hurt me the most. i included my experiences with older men because of recent convos on r kelly. these situations are happening everyday and they are real & serious. believe us!" ‚Äì crystal lipscomb parker

#allcrystal #muterkelly #believewomen

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
fashion shines a spotlight on important issues!
today we observe and celebrate dr. martin luther king jr. and his advocacy for rectifying injustices for all. dr. king, despite the dangers and consequences never stopped his efforts to educate and promote fairness amongst all races and classes. his efforts focused on economic disparities, equality and peace. today‚Äôs fashion blog is dedicated to the legacy of dr. martin luther king jr. and the importance of keeping his message alive.
there have been many fashion moments that make the world take notice and emphasizes dr. king‚Äôs message of ‚Äúpeace over violence‚Äù. this is evident in various movements such as ‚Äúdenim day‚Äù which was sparked by a rape case in italy in which the victim wore tight jeans and was made by her attacker to help him remove her jeans. it was declared that by helping to remove the jeans it was no longer rape but consensual sex. the women in the italian parliament immediately protested by wearing jeans to work.  another example is the ‚Äò#metoo and time‚Äôs up‚Äù movement, as many actors wore black at the 2018 golden globes to protest against sexual harassment, assault and supporting women workers‚Äô rights in the workplace.
we have used clothes to shine a spotlight on important issues such as racism, gay pride, anti-terrorism, and the list goes on and on, all in an effort of displaying a peaceful protest. a way of saying, ‚Äúlook at me! even if i am silenced, i will speak through my clothes and proudly state my message!‚Äù make no mistake, the use of fashion as a social and political tool is increasingly popular and a display of how we carry on the legacy of a man who continued to promote change through peace and non-violence. happy birthday dr. king! #mlk, #mlkbirthday, #ihaveadream, #together, #peace, #changegonnacome

quotes by: martin luther king jr.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

now a growing group of women, after years of silence, are forming a unified movement advocating for change. "thai women are taught to say yes - we are groomed to please others. men don‚Äôt ask what women want, they just take it." it is time to talk about consent.

text_retweet:
i'm reposting this because it is such an integral part of who i am. some of y'all are aware that ive been subject to multiple acts of sexual violence, which is difficult to talk about and difficult to accept, but again, it is a foundation of who i am as a person. i've spent years bitter, scarred, asking why, wondering what i did to deserve it. 
i'm here to tell you that i did not deserve it, and if you've faced it, i assure you: neither did you. it doesn't matter if you were four years old or forty years old, this stuff sticks around and haunts you, even once you find forgiveness, even once you find peace. your voice in these rape and assault conversations matters, and i am here to listen. you matter; i'm sorry; let us find solutions together. 
to those interacting with rape/assault victims: please listen. please be quiet. please hurt with us. do not pretend to understand; please do not pretend to get it. you do not. end of story. please hold our hurt in the palms of your hands as if it's the most precious gift in the world, because it is. this scar tissue, this piece of our souls, is incredibly vulnerable. take care of it.

text:
on this day in 1973, roe vs wade was decided in favor of roe in a 7-2 decision that enacted her right to personal privacy illustrated in the 9th and 14th amendments in order to pursue an abortion up until the 3rd trimester. "roe," otherwise known as norma mccorvey disavowed her position on abortion in 1994, but, as of now, the case is regarded as settled law. mccorvey, who wound up having the child and putting it up for adoption, initially falsely asserted that she had been raped in order to obtain a legal abortion in texas, but as there was no police report, she was denied under state law. the decision has become a hot button issue for the left and the right ever since.

text:
before i learned to see the world in full color, when my vision was still limited by the grey hues of pain and fear, i couldn‚Äôt imagine what a life lived in brilliance and peace felt like.  i only knew a one-dimensional world with other captives like me, all of us seeking the way out through a door seemingly hidden in plain view.
it‚Äôs starts with a specks of light, and as that grows we see color begin to show itself.  there is hope.  there is love.  there is purpose to life. pretty soon, our eyes are so adjusted to the color of all that life can be, we don‚Äôt give the grey much notice when it comes around.
embrace this life for everything it has for you.  live your life in full color!
#lifelive #suicideprevention #recoverywriter #adultsurvivor #metoo #itgetsbetter  #mentalhealthrecovery #mentalhealthawareness.  #incestsurvivor  #ptsd #emotionalrecovery #hope #faith

text: super personal post ‚ÄºÔ∏è wow, hey instagram it‚Äôs been a really long time. i haven‚Äôt done a personal post in a while. why was i gone for so long? welp, here it goes. early october, i was raped. it took me a really long time to even admit to what happened. i kept making excuses. the saddest part is that, this was the second time. i ignored the first time. he had stopped after a min or so, it wasn‚Äôt rape. i literally was telling myself it wasn‚Äôt his fault bc i was highly medicated and couldn‚Äôt really fight him off me- i didn‚Äôt make the no clear enough. when it happened the second time- it killed me. i know to die is to have no heartbeat, but your soul can die in other ways. mine did that day. i ignored it for a couple weeks but it eventually beat me so far down that i stopped talking to tons of people, i stay in my room (in bed) for most of the day, i stopped using social media except an occasional log in, for over two months, i fought with friends, etc. i‚Äôm still on the mend. i also had to add another medication to my already 4 pills a day. this wasn‚Äôt a violent rape, it didn‚Äôt physically hurt me up until a few days ago when i found out i have to have surgery, bc of that rape. i thought it was almost over and now i have to deal with this part. rape has been in the media a lot lately. people really say some crazy shit about it but let me be clear. rape is rape. period. no girls asks for this shit. no woman wants to feel so neglected that she can no longer have sex bc you were too horny to stop. no woman wants these scars. one way i self harm, is with sex. i abuse myself with it. and not even i ask to be raped. this has taken my soul from me and i‚Äôve done nothing but fight to get it back. please, help put an end to rape. be active. be a friend. no one deserves to go through rape but they def don‚Äôt deserve to feel alone. if you ever need someone to talk to if you‚Äôve been through something similar i‚Äôm always here for you and i‚Äôm so so sorry. one last thing, you can‚Äôt define someone else‚Äôs rape. so don‚Äôt try. it‚Äôs not your story. don‚Äôt try to be an author in that kinda horror. #metoo #metoomovement

i cant wait for all this court stuff to be over.
yes i said court stuff.
if you know me and we are close i'm sorry i didn't say anything.
a few months ago i saw sexually #assaulted. yep you heard me.
i was lucky enough for my precious babies to be away.
this creature didn't know how to keep their hands to themselves.
i said no and fought back.
as hard as i could.
i went straight to the #police.
even tho someone i told doubted me and said it was my fault for putting myself in a situation. but the thing is guys and gals. i wasn't #drunk. it wasn't 3 am waking home. i was at a friend's of a friend's house with them. i was wearing jeans, t-shirt and a giant @devilskinnz hoodie.
after this he kept texting and calling. i blocked his number. he made various #facebook accounts to get in contact.
he found out where i lived. yes he sure fucking did.
he had been stalking me just around #xmas until early this saturday morning.
when my children where at their grandmother's, i had banging on my window. i was scared. thought it was the wind and it was person lurking around my house. called the cops the person had vanished.
cops told me to be careful. as it was still an open case.
on #friday afternoon i got a call. saying this person had not been home for curfew, later that evening early saturday morning. there where banging on all my windows yes my windows aroun 1 am.
this time my #kids where here
i was quiet as a mouse could be. called the police. in this time i heard screaming. and in this time. what was said was scary and made me feel so sick. he said if i where to testify and stand up in court he was going to not only me my children. i was so lucky that it was #wellington cup day here in the hutt. and there where cops everywhere.
also the person i was speaking to on the phone was recording our conversation and heard herself what he was saying.
2 mins went by which seemed like a life time. a mufti car turned up no lights what so ever and arrested him on the spot.
and yep it was this person who assaulted.
he plead not guilty in court on monday.
even though evidence points to him.
lucky for me (not so lucky) what he said was used against him.. t

she watched me up and down

instead her friends told me "she feels abused." i'm like i ain't going down by no #metoo.
thought she would be quick to hop in the coupe,
but then she stood me up like i was 3'2.
had to take a sip of my gin and juice
placed it calmly right on the bar stool.
grabbed her by the arm and said "look what you gon make me do." friends pulled her back as we head to the bathroom.
i pushed those girls out like some #fakenews.
she made me so upset, i told her not to move.
told her stop shouting she gon spoil the mood.
tears roll down her face as i start to groove.

got really pumped as she got loose.
just then i turned around and i turned blue
barrel pointed at me, i'm like "don't shoot!"
"i got a lot of money" "keep this between me and you."
i got shot twice and the place turned into a zoo.
she ran and i passed out without a clue.

understand that women aren't safe no matter what they do.
even if they're out in large groups.
look out for predators, they have a way they move.
most importantly let's stop domestic and sexual abuse!

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
according to the times, cambridge analytica bought the data from aleksandr kogan, a russian-american academic. kogan, who told facebook he was conducting academic research, built a facebook personality quiz app called "thisisyourdigitalife." when users downloaded the app, it scraped all of their available facebook data, including their friends, their likes and where they lived.

more than a quarter-million facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. by prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

throughout 2015 and into 2016, the cruz campaign paid cambridge analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like iowa and new hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer".
.
in december 2015, the same month the guardian revealed cambridge analytica and kogan's data harvesting practices, cruz campaign spokesman rick tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field." despite tyler's claim that the cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying cambridge analytic until june of that year, a month after cruz suspended his campaign. after cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with trump, supporting him through november's general election against hillary clinton.

stephen young
dallas observer

in 2014, steve bannon ‚Äì then executive chairman of the ‚Äúalt-right‚Äù news network breitbart ‚Äì was christopher wylie‚Äôs boss. and robert mercer, the secretive us hedge-fund billionaire and republican donor, was cambridge analytica‚Äôs investor. and the idea they bought into was to bring big data and social media to an established military methodology ‚Äì ‚Äúinformation operations‚Äù ‚Äì then turn it on the us electorate.

cambridge analytica‚Äôs parent company, scl, had won contracts with the us state department and was pitching to the pentagon, and wylie was genuinely freaked out. - it‚Äôs insane, he told me one night. - the company has created psychological profiles of 230 million americans. and now they want to work with the pentagon? it‚Äôs like nixon on steroids.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
cardi b claps back at conservative political commentator stephanie hamill for ‚Äútwerk‚Äù video criticism ‚Ä¢ #cardib #twerk #citygirls ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ 
cardi b is fed up with the far right. following a now-viral rant against trump's government shut down and a public tiff with right-wing political pundit tomi lahren (that ended with cardi telling lahren she would "dog walk" her ‚Äî iconic), cardi is now clapping back conservative journalist stephanie hamill after she criticized cardi and the city girls' new "twerk" video.

this saga begins with a tweet hamill posted yesterday (jan. 21). "in the era of #metoo how exactly does this empower women?" hamill asked while sharing the "twerk" video. "leftists, @iamcardib , feel free to chime in. thx .." cardi clapped right back the following morning (jan. 22) and kept it classy while making a very clear point. "it says to women that i can wear and not wear what ever i want. do w.e i want and that no still means no," cardi wrote on twitter. "so stephanie chime in..if i twerk and be half naked does that mean i deserve to get raped and molested ? i want to know what a conservative woman like you thinks." shortly afterwards, hamill once again responded to cardi's tweet. "i agree, no means no, no matter what! but this video, & others like this sexually objectify women," hamill replied. "i think this hurts all women & the cause. we're not sex objects! clearly we see things differently, (maybe i'm just a hater bc i can't twerk ) come on my show, debate me!" cardi has yet to respond to the offer. (via xxl)

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
for some reason this one had to be written today üôèüèºwarning: this poem has sensitive content and a few swear words. it came in response to my own personal experiences of groping and sexual assaults and as a result of a conversation with a friend regarding #metoocampaign 
poetry always helps me to get things in perspective. it's easy to feel a victim in these situations but if this has happened to you too, you must know you did nothing wrong. there's nothing wrong with you. you absolutely didn't ask for it. if you are having trouble moving on, go get some therapy so you are free to live your life again. you may find help here:¬†https://rapecrisis.org.uk/get-help// the poem was written from the perspective of a woman being assaulted by a man because that was my personal experience. this is in no way an attack on men. i love men. real men. and i'm well aware that men experience this kind of abuse too. this poem really describes anyone of any race or gender that abuses their power sexually or otherwise... you‚Ä®with your wandering eyes‚Ä®and groping hands

you ain't no man... was‚Ä®minding my own business‚Ä®if you please.. no‚Ä®not today or any day‚Ä®don't subject me to your sleaze

get‚Ä®your fucking dirty fingers‚Ä®out of my crutch

stop‚Ä®polluting me with your‚Ä®sickening touch

how‚Ä®dare you think you can enter‚Ä®the most sacred part of me

stealing‚Ä®my warmth and tenderness‚Ä®just because you like what you see

no...you ain't no man
a real man doesn't take‚Ä®just because he can

a real man has honour and respect‚Ä®he supports and encourages‚Ä®doesn't judge, jibe, goad and neglect

text: this has been a really hard end of the year. back in september i publicly admitted on twitter my step-father molested me. my mother responded that she knew about the beatings (one where his navy friend had to drag him off of me when he was drunkenly kicking and slapping me against a stairwell) but didn't know about the molestation, so i must be a liar or "misremembered". i am not a liar, i remeber every horrible touch and threat and crying into my silky pillow as he touched me. if a man beats your child what makes you think he wouldn't molest her too? soon after our twitter conversation she stopped talking to me, liking my tweets and then i noticed she unfollowed me. i've written poems and published comics about her strong womanly influence on me but i can't reach her with my words any longer, so i've given up. stiffler's birthday came and went without comment, my beautiful cat's passing was met with silence and distance. my youngest step-sisters, who are more influenced by my mom and their dad/my step-dad than me, stopped talking to me too. i don't blame them. i know what it's like to be out in the cold if you speak out of turn. i just hope they know i love them and only ever wish the best for them. the day i left home at 17 i threatened my step-father that if he ever laid hands (beating, slapping, kicking, spanking, molesting) on my sisters i would come back and kill him. i feel the same now. you cannot hurt them because of me, and you cannot hurt me any longer. it's disheartening being in the #metoo era and seeing some of your family seem apathetic and even angry at you for speaking out, but i will not be silent any longer, no matter the cost. i'm sorry i was molested by him, but i was, and i will not be a victim, i'd rather be a survivor. i love all of them except for him and that will never change, but my heart is shattered by how harsh the world is to survivors. i've been comforted by stiffler, legba and the beautiful lights abounding, but it's been tough and horrible and so full of heartache. i love you, i love you, i love you and that will never change, i won't let his perverse behaviors change my love for you, even if you hate me. i'm so sorry.

text:
* trigger warning * -  abuse , sexual harassment 
i feel although i have finally gained the confidence to share this picture from 9 years ago.. 9 years ago today, was a time midway through my sexual and psychological abuse which in total had been ongoing for about 4 years since i was 17 years old.. it was the single most traumatic time of my life and today i still question how i survived and where i found my strength to finally.. finally let go of my emotions and let go of my abuser. 
at this time of my life i was absolutely powerless and everybody including my ' fp ' of 13years at the time refused to believe me .. asking for evidence or " proof " of my experiences.. i thank my lucky stars everyday for my life and the very air that fill my lungs.. i suppose the message i am trying to send out in the world is .. if someone is in trouble , love them , care for them for exactly who they are.. don't let go unless you absolutely have to and you have every right to do that.. your stronger then you think you are.. let go of those emotions that control you, stay strong and don't give up on yourself.  be every bit of a warrior you know you are and keep fighting ü•ä

text:
his sense of humour defines him, always ready with a wise-crack, or joke to lighten the mood, bring on the laughter and break the proverbial ice. the urban dictionary refers to it as a 'fun way to work sex into any conversation,' scott capitalized on the timing and popularity of the 'that's what she said' phrase, offering it up as a surefire way of making a grand entrance and wowing the audience with his sharp sense of humour. a phrase that has roots that date back to early 1900's, the twss has become the subject of controversy as some move to take a closer look at the double entendre and the implications of sexual innuendo, particularly in light of the #metoo movement. 
has twss run its course? perhaps. does political correctness, spell the end of innuendo, 'vulgar' colloquialism and sexualized humour? it's highly unlikely. some may find fault in the four word expression, others may find humour, what's certain is that scott intended no harm when he uttered the now taboo four words. #scotteastwood #stephencolbert #twss #taboo #pc #humour #funny #sexualized #offended #controversy #innuendo #doubleentendre #wit @scotteastwood

..
too much over the past 18months has occurred, i have had insufficient support emotionally and in regards to my #chronicpain and #chronicillness - the medical professionals have discriminated against me, neglected my care and caused me extra pain and suffering. i wouldn't have a severe chronic pain issue if doctor's actually investigated my pain in the first couple of months. the violent rape may have caused the injury, but medical negligence is the reason it is an issue now days, amongst various things.
..

..

text:
there have been a lot of marches and a lot of calls to action just in this past week. and we are here for it! our feminism intersects all recent events and we are standing up for human dignity every chance we get. we hope you are, too.

please remember to take care of yourself. take a break when you need to. rest, breathe, pray, run, scream, do whatever it is you need to do. burnout is a real thing and it does no one any good. but even more than recharging so you can fight another day, please recharge for yourself. you are worth the time and energy it takes to find your inner peace. you are one of the people we are fighting for. don't push yourself past what you can handle. 
i'm going to be completely honest with y'all for a minute. i made this graphic because i needed it. i'm burned out, too. so i'm going to try my best to follow the advice i'm giving you all. :-) self care for everyone!

text:
meet andrea alejandra gonzales -  an 18 year-old indigenous-latina queer activist! ‚ú® ‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äîandrea is an advocate for marginalized youth and serves as the director of operations of the student led non-profit, youth over guns (@youthoverguns). andrea advocates for change that's inclusive of underserved communities of color and empowers youth to fight for life-saving policies. ‚Å£
‚Å£
after the tragic parkland shooting in florida, andrea led the national school walkout at her own high school and was an organizer for ‚Äúmarch for our lives ny‚Äù - an event where youth can discuss sensible gun control, teenage suicide and violence prevention strategies with government officials in albany. ‚Å£
‚Å£
andrea has also been at the forefront of several other movements and has protested against rape culture at the capitol in d.c., marched in harlem against police brutality and has rallied against the mistreatment of immigrants by ice officers. andrea has even posed as a model for a series of photos regarding rape culture that have been displayed at the metropolitan museum of art and was recognized by news outlets like fox news and cbs. andrea  currently implements restorative justice strategies at the staten island youth justice center and studies political science at baruch college in new york city. @mestizawomanist  #represent
name: Represent

22.
a historical figure
_
a woman's rage
is earned,
like respect. 
history speaks of
women cautiously
spinning a web 
of deceit. 
virtues;
beauty, grace
an unholy disgrace. 
yet key elements
remain forgotten.
a virgin beauty
taken and defiled,
a sacred crime
repeated. 
yet history,
myth,
or legend blame 
her. 
beauty now spoiled, 
a godly act 
defines her;
we see the gorgon
now so clearly,
she has earned
her rage.

text:
these pictures popped up in my facebook memories a few weeks back and something caught me in my tracks: yes, obviously my dress fits better now üíÉ and my hair has more volume. but, look at that confidence. like...do you see those weirdo smiles?? üëÄ and awkward body language?? (i mean aside from that second picture when i am obviously drunk and feelin' it ü§£) _
_

anyway, i thought it would be cool to do a different type of flashback/transformation thing with the same dress. not just noticing of the difference in fit, but the difference in how i carry myself and why 
_
2012.... i had already dyed my hair jet black in an attempt to erase that one awful year at the university. my natural light brown hair reminded me of that time. does that sound silly to you?? cause at the time it seemed like the best answer and something i could control (this is also why i will never go back to my natural color, fyi) 
_
but that time unfortunately wasn't magically erased by a new hair color, and i had a lot of mental things to work through. i blamed myself for being raped and the terrible domino effect that occurred afterward. for years, i pretended to be someone i thought everyone would approve of to "earn their trust and respect" (again, for events that weren't truly my fault), but i became very lost. it took years to rediscover who the fuck i am and what i stood for. hell, i'm still figuring it out sometimes ‚ù§ 
_

the total wierdo you know today took a loooonnngggg time to rediscover and own that weirdness. it's been a long road to this mile mark. 
_
 when i look at these pictures, i see all of that growth- not just the looser dress and fried greenish hair- and i am proud of who she is ‚úäüèΩ

text:
her long hair is her glory, form fitting (shown), & hush, hush by @elipeck_ are on view now in enough. reception is this friday! don't miss them.

artist statement: "throughout our lives, the words and actions of our friends, families, authority figures, and strangers influence the way that we perceive our bodies. we are taught by culture how our bodies compare to ideals, and from a young age, are taught to love and cherish our unique figures, or to be ashamed of ourselves; to hide parts of ourselves, or to show off.

in this series, i seek to explore my own developing relationship with my body in light of specific influences on my self-image, namely the culture that i grew up in that enforced a strict role of femininity that emphasized modesty, while also teaching me to cater to the male gaze." #metoo #mcaexhibition #enough

text:
i didn't break when at the age of seventeen it happened to me when i was out with an older person whom i trusted. 
i didn't break when his hands muffled my voice and his weight lay there crushing me. 
i didn't break when my body felt limp and i couldn't get up. 
i didn't break when i felt like i was going to choke on my own tears and finally die, which actually seemed like a feasible option then. 
i didn't break when after it was all, over he smirked at me and looked me in the eye and said ‚Äúno one will ever believe you‚Äù.
i didn't break when my parents blamed a  victim for being out in the dark and they were so thankful that their girls were really obedient. 
i didn't break when i was with my lover and i froze in the moment and couldn't bring myself to enjoy the act ever again. 
i didn't break when i followed countless other stories of rape which occurred almost daily. 
i didn't break when my family was against me when i wanted to file a report in fear of destroying their image and ruining chances of me getting a decent marriage proposal. 
it was only the inspector's question asking me what i wore that day, was what broke me.

text:
on sunday i enacted a guerrilla protest/performance piece at the art institute of chicago in response to their current exhibition of roger weston‚Äôs collection of 17th century ukiyo-e paintings from japan. the women depicted in these pieces are referred to as beauties who were ‚Äúcourtesans, geishas, actors, or women in scenes of everyday life‚Äù in the floating world, a pleasure quarter similar to what we know as the red-light district. the narrative offered by the museum focuses on the fact that the women possessed great beauty and impeccable style. the museum fails to provide viewers the brutal truth. 
along with several other volunteers, we played an alternate audio tour through our iphones and projected it throughout the exhibition to supplement the audio tour the museum created that fails to reveal the horrific living conditions endured by the women and children, who were actually sex slaves. listen to the truth by following the link in my profile. there is a form on my website you can use to contact the museum if you also feel that museums should stop hiding the truth about the work they present.

text:
as i marvelled at this painting, i overheard a girl as she walked passed, "ugh, it's only jesus." ...and my question is, how did we get here? that this generation and those after would get so disgusted with jesus?
‚Ä¢
my thought is because there are a lot of really really religious people out there that either have a lot of rules or say you're going to hell because you look a certain way. and unfortunately showing love and handing out grace is never in the mix they sell.
so, instead of being critical, you love each person as is. that you as a human (and have many flaws yourself) overlook things that you don't quite agree with and show them how jesus loves you to them and let his ultimate love iron out what needs to be ironed out in them.
‚Ä¢
how can we, as the hands and feet of jesus, show others that jesus himself is more relatable to them and wants to know more about them too? that yes, he did preform miracles, like you preform on a stage. he was a hipster carpenter in his time like the way your hipster self becomes one with the wood and builds a coffee table with hairpin legs. he turned water into wine, like you want to do with turning water into an artisan cup of coffee. he was savage as he spoke like you are when you present your rebuttal on the debate team. he made a feast out of 9 loaves of bread and two fish like you do with hello fresh boxes.
‚Ä¢
he's not so out of touch. he is relatable. we need to be relatable too.

text:
catch the last stop of this leg of #hikingmyfeelingstour: santa monica @rei, i'm coming for you on friday at 7pm!

if you're new around these parts, welcome! the #hikingmyfeelings speaking + hiking tour explores the mind-body connection that i (@sydneyunfiltered) found on the #transcatalinatrail. i connect the dots between a sexual assault i survived 12+ years ago and my #type2diabetes diagnosis, and all the changes in my life since i started managing this disease. i was able to recreate myself outside, reclaim parts of my body and dignity that were stolen from me during the assault, and rebuild a life out of the ashes when it all came crashing down in early 2018. don't forget, we have group hikes tied to each of these speaking stops so let's talk it out on friday night and walk it out on saturday! and if you're curious about #vanlife, ruby (our van) will be available for tours after the speaking + hiking events!

more rei dates:
did you hear? we are taking this talk across the country! we will post more dates as we confirm them, and if you want us to swing through your town, let us know which store is closest to you in the comments. 
visit hikingmyfeelings.com and subscribe to get info about the new tour dates, group hikes, and other fun events we are putting together this year! 
bonus: we are hosting our first #transcatalinatrail backpacking trip across catalina island march 4-10 and we'd love to have you join us. dm me for more info!
name: Live Your Best Life Outside

text:
recently i was alerted to an exhibition at the art institute of chicago that presents roger weston‚Äôs collection of 17th century ukiyo-e paintings from japan. the museum refers to the ‚Äúbeauties‚Äù in these portraits as ‚Äúcourtesans, geishas, actors, or women in scenes of everyday life‚Äù in the floating world, a pleasure quarter similar to what we know as the red-light district. the narrative offered by the museum focuses on the fact that the women possessed great beauty and impeccable style. the museum fails to provide viewers the whole story. 
the audio tour created by the art institute of chicago does not mention the brutal living conditions the women endured. one ipad in a corner of the exhibition offers an altered narrative of what it was like for the child sex slaves, who are referred to as ‚Äúkamuro,‚Äù revealing only that children as young as seven were contracted to brothels by their impoverished families, stating ‚Äúgirls who showed promise were educated and trained to assume the role of courtesan, the highest level of prostitute.‚Äù only one sentence on a wall label states that there was a wall and moat that prevented women from leaving the pleasure district. 
the truth:

many of the sex slaves were beaten, starved, suffered from sexually transmitted diseases, and if slaves died while imprisoned, they were buried in mass graves. brothel keepers sometimes kept the women they owned in a box. 
i created an alternate audio tour that provides the truth about these artworks and includes an interview with dr. amy stanley, a historian of early modern and modern japan.

please listen to the alternate audio by following the link in my profile. #correcthistory #correctarthistory #artinstituteofchicago #floatingworlds #westoncollections #rogerweston #fleshvasesfordickflowers #metoo
name: Michelle Hartney

the audio tour created by the a institute of chicago does not mention the brutal living conditions the women endured. one ipad in a corner of the exhibition offers an altered narrative of what it was like for the child sex slaves, who are referred to as ‚Äúkamuro,‚Äù revealing only that children as young as seven were contracted to brothels by their impoverished families, stating ‚Äúgirls who showed promise were educated and trained to assume the role of couesan, the highest level of prostitute.‚Äù only one sentence on a wall label states that there was a wall and moat that prevented women from leaving the pleasure district. 
the truth:

many of the sex slaves were beaten, starved, suffered from sexually transmitted diseases, and if slaves died while imprisoned, they were buried in mass graves. brothel keepers sometimes kept the women they owned in a box. 
i created an alternate audio tour that provides the truth about these aworks and includes an interview with dr. amy stanley, a historian of early modern and modern japan.

please listen to the alternate audio by following the link in my profile.

text:
heavy post. take care of yourself. üíïüíïüíï cn: personal trauma and healing work

ohhhhhmyfuckinggawwwwwd.

solidarity to everyone in recovery from sexual trauma. i am with you. i am for you. you are not alone.

the intensity is normal. the pain and rage and grief and heartache and triggered moments even after *years* of healing is normal. the sensitivity. the struggle to trust, to believe safety is possible, all normal. healing is nonlinear.

i cried before and during therapy, and afterwards, sobbed my heart out. 
i didn't dissociate, and i'm astonished at my presence with and compassion toward myself the whole time today.

time to rehydrate. and rest. and write a loveletter to my self.

text:
from 2005 - 2009, the women in the mennonite colony of molotschna (manitoba colony, bolivia) were waking up daily in pain, bruised, and often bleeding. for the years this happened, they believed it was a punishment from god, or that the various young girls and women had gone mad. until 2009...when it was found out that 8 men of their community, possibly more, had been sneaking into these women‚Äôs homes, tranquilizing them with an animal spray, and raping them in their sleep. ‚Ä¢
in 2011, the 8 men were given long prison sentences.
‚Ä¢
in 2013, it was reported instances of similar nature were still occurring.
‚Ä¢
miriam toews novel ‚Äúwomen talking‚Äù is a compelling read, exploring the real life situation with a fictional reaction. beautifully written, and so important to our modern day toews explores ideas of femininity, religion and taking a stand. ‚Ä¢
i highly recommend this read! ‚Ä¢
#booksofinstagram #book #bookstagram #booklovers #feminism #metoo #read #reads #readersofinstagram #readers #reader #fiction #booklove

text:
| they were wrong | 
you are woman they said, 
stay at home and make some bread, 
don‚Äôt spread your wings, spread your legs, 
you can‚Äôt change the world, no one cares, 
you have to fit in the society, be prepared, 
don‚Äôt wear that, be scared, 
men they said will eat you alive,
there is no space for rights, you have to survive, 
religion doesn‚Äôt help either, 
it‚Äôs a web and man is the spider, 
you are known as the weaker sex,
let men make the money and pay the tax, 
while you sit at home and wax,
it‚Äôs only recently that you got the voting rights, 
don‚Äôt you expect to see the light, 
men will burry you without a fight. ... doesn‚Äôt the first verse make your blood boil, 
but the reality is that women have been treated like that, 
they are now united and taking a stand, 
trust me, #metoo is just the beginning my friend, 
if the system is broken, they will build another one, 
like that cheeky advertisement once said, 
why should boys have all the fun. - qais parkar

text:
about the book 
in the woman in the mirror, author evelyn mejil provides a vivid portrait of her courageous mind meeting her painful memories, her valiant heart overcoming her shameful unworthiness, and her bold spirit overpowering her relentless fear.
in this account, mejil shares an uncensored description of how she overcomes her past when she discovers an inconspicuous truth while traveling the world in search for answers to silence her nightmares and heal her pain. hidden in the eyes of the woman reflected in the mirror, she sees the answers stood where she buried her painful past, and to find them there is only one journey left to take, a journey within.
the woman in the mirror tells how once she goes beyond the memories and faces her demons, she finally discovers her true being and vividly recounts how her false self, the identity birthed in the lies of her past, collapses. shattering the iron grip of her past, she heals and brings forth a new story. mejil presents the unadulterated expression of her most powerful self, the authentic self.
order your copy today by visiting: evelynmejil.com link in bio üîù

text:
chris brown and two members of his team have been arrested by french police after a woman claims she was raped by the singer in a hotel.

french authorities confirmed, brown has been detained and is in custody for alleged aggravated rape and narcotics offenses. authorities went on to say he is being processed, which is the french version of being arrested and booked. 
the woman says she met brown overnight between january 15-16 at club le crystal and then headed back to the mandarin oriental hotel with the singer where she claims to have been raped.

investigators have two days to decide to file preliminary charges or to let brown go.

chris was spotted at le cirque club in paris saturday night -- just three days after the alleged rape -- with ammika harris, a woman who he is reportedly dating.

brown was prosecuted for felony assault and making criminal threats after he brutally attacked rihanna in los angeles. the beating left rihanna with visible facial injuries to her eyes and mouth which required hospitalization.

brown later pled guilty to a felony and was sentenced to community service, 5 years probation and domestic violence counseling.

brown was sued back in may by a woman who claimed she was raped at a party at the singer's home. the woman claimed brown supplied party attendees with molly, cocaine and weed and that it was one of his friends who raped her. 
the lapd investigated the woman's claim after she filed a report, but could not determine if the sex was forced or consensual. the lawsuit is ongoing.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
chris brown allegedly raped a woman in a hotel dressing room for 25-30 minutes and it was "brutal and violent" -- so says closer magazine, which posted an article claiming to have interviewed the alleged victim.

closer, which broke the story brown was being investigated for rape, calls the woman by a pseudonym -- karima -- a 24-year-old model who told the mag she met brown at the mandarin oriental hotel in paris on january 15 at around 10:30 pm and then went to a nightclub. 
karima told closer at 4 am brown and his crew wanted to return to the hotel, and she said she was tired but they convinced her to go back to the mandarin with a group of people.

she says once inside his suite, she went to the bathroom, brown followed her and "catches me by the right arm. he makes me enter a sort of dressing room.  he closed the door ... it lasted 25 - 30 minutes." she describes the alleged rape as "brutal and violent." she says she was then "abused" by one of brown's friends and a bodyguard.

karima says she went to cops 2 days later, adding she was scared but ultimately decided she didn't want brown to "be able to do the same things to other girls." someone connected to brown tells us the singer was never alone with the alleged victim and says chris' girlfriend, amika harris, was in the hotel room the whole time.  he says there were more than 20 people in the room "hanging out" and listening to music brown was playing on his iphone.
.
.
.
.

text:
it's apparently only tuesday. spoke today at the #feu conference on sexual harassment. great to see the action our unions are taking to turn #metoo into cultural change in our workplaces. freelances form part of those increasingly non traditional workplaces but so many don't realise that they do have rights to be protected from harassment at work. it's a slow process.

yesterday started off discussions on how we can address the barriers that women photographers and videographers face in the industry. plans are also underway to launch the #nuj women's network.

watch this space.

oh, and it's snowing.
